Criminal Law – Offences – Remote Gambling Act – Common Gaming Houses Act – Organised Crime Act

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing – Principles

21 September 2022

### Senior District Judge Bala Reddy:

1       The present case arises from illicit gambling activities facilitated by the accused, Ng Eng Thiam (“**Accused**”) over an extended period of more than 3 years (_i.e._ from sometime in 2013 to 27 November 2016) in an elaborate cross-border illegal betting syndicate involving multiple hierarchical chains of command, significant betting amounts and copycat Singapore Pools (Private) Limited (“**SPL**”) lottery games “4-Digit Games” (“**4D**”) and “TOTO Games” (“**TOTO**”) offered by the syndicate to the public. The four proceeded charges against the Accused are as follows:

> (a)     one charge under s 5(a) of the Common Gaming Houses Act (Cap 49, 1985 Rev Ed) (“**CGHA**”) for assisting one PW3 Lean Kay Cheong (“**PW3 LKC**”) in carrying on public lotteries for the SPL’s 4D and TOTO games;

> (b)     one charge under s 9(1)(a) of the Remote Gambling Act 2014 (Act No. 34 of 2014) (“**RGA**”) for managing remote gambling activities _inter alia_ receiving and collecting bets via remote communication channels, handing the bet amounts to PW3 LKC and distributing the prize monies;

> (c)     one charge under s 11 of the Organised Crime Act 2015 (No. 26 of 2015) (“**OCA**”) for dealing with property illegally obtained by an organised criminal group; and

> (d)     one charge under s 5 of the OCA for acting as an agent of a locally-linked organised criminal group providing remote gambling services with PW3 LKC and Seah Ee Lam (“**PW2 SEL**”).

2       I convicted the Accused on all four proceeded charges and sentenced the Accused to a global sentence of 28 months’ imprisonment and fine of $46,000 (in default 10 weeks’ imprisonment) with the sentences for DAC-913327-2019 and DAC-913331-2019 running consecutively. The sentences imposed are set out in the table as follows:

## Salient Facts

4       The facts of the case are uncomplicated and involves a syndicated remote gambling operation headed in Malaysia. The syndicate collected illicit 4D and TOTO bets from the public (“**Punters**”) through, _inter alia_, “_agents_”, “_master agents_” and “_runners_” who facilitated remote gambling activities.

5       The illegal gambling operations mimicked the licensed 4D and TOTO operations ran by SPL, an exempt operator under the RGA.

6       Under the illicit gambling operations, bets were placed on 4-digit number draws for 4D and six number draws for TOTO conducted by SPL three times and twice a week, respectively. The syndicate did not conduct its own draws but instead relied on SPL’s draws to pick the winners for the illegal 4D and TOTO games.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

7       The syndicate, for example, offered punters the option to place big bets at $1.60 and small bets at $0.70 for the syndicate’s illicit 4D operations. The prize monies determined by the syndicate on big bets were $4,000 (“1st Prize”), $2,000 (“2nd Prize”), $1,000 (“3rd Prize”), $500 (ten “Starter Prizes”) and approximately $100 (ten “Consolation Prizes”).[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) The prize monies for the small bets were $3,000, $2,000 and $1,000 for the first, second and third prizes, respectively, with no consolation or starter prizes.[^3] Bets were placed via phone by messaging a number in Malaysia.

8       PW3 LKC a “_master agent_” led the remote gambling organised crime group by receiving bets from agents and punters on his account and communicated them via phone to a Malaysian number. PW2 SEL in turn worked as PW3 LKC’s “_runner_” collecting and delivering money from agents. The Accused was an “_agent_”, under PW3 LKC, receiving bets, communicating bets, collecting bets and distributing bets to punters. Collectively, PW3 LKC, PW2 SEL and the Accused formed an organised criminal group dealing with illegally obtained property.

## Prosecution’s case

11     The Prosecution adduced the evidence of six witnesses who provided oral testimony in court. I set out the evidence of the witnesses briefly as follows:

### PW2 – SEL

## Defence’s Case

31     At the close of the Prosecution’s case, the Accused elected to testify in his defence. He also called his brother to testify on his behalf.

32     The crux of the Defence’s case revolved around the assertions that the Accused was a “punter” and not an “agent” in the illicit gambling operations and that the monies transferred between the Accused and PW3 LKC were friendly loans between friends.

### DW 1 – Accused

33     The Accused testified that he was a businessman. He acted as a director and shareholder of five companies Newave Fashion Private Limited (“**Newave**”), Tri-M Resources Pte Limited (“**Tri-M**”), A Formation Construction Private Limited (“**A Formation**”), Joo Chin Vending Private Limited (“**Joo Chin**”) and Eng Investment Private Limited (“**Eng Investment**”) (collectively referred to as the “**Companies**”). Newave is a spectacle business. Tri-M and A Formation are in the sand and construction business, respectively. Joo Chin and Eng Investment are investment companies.

34     The Accused stated that his average annual income for 2015 and 2016 was $50,000 to $60,000 per annum. The Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore Notices of Assessment recorded the Accused’s annual assessable income as $71,449, $79,164 and $76,151 in 2016, 2017 and 2018, respectively. The Accused was unable to affirmatively point to any other sources of income in 2016[\[note: 59\]](#Ftn_59) and confirmed that apart from the $1,500 per month he received from New Wave between 2013 and 2016, he received no other monies as a director and shareholder of the Companies.[^60]

35     At the time of his arrest on 27 November 2016, the Accused claimed that he had around a total of $100,000 to $200,000 accumulated in his DBS, OCBC and UOB bank accounts over an extended period of time.[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61)

36     In respect of his involvement in the illegal gambling syndicate, the Accused claimed that he was merely a punter who placed personal bets with PW3 LKC. In particular, he claimed that he was good friends with PW3 LKC[\[note: 62\]](#Ftn_62) and stated that he started frequently placing 4D bets with PW3 LKC’s female assistant approximately two to three years prior to his arrest. He stated that he usually placed bets of $100 to $200 per draw and sometimes bets of over $1000.[^63] These bet amounts were handed over to PW3 LKC’s assistant. Curiously, the Accused was unable to recall the names of the alleged female assistant he placed his bets with or the assistant who collected the bet amounts[^64] (although he recognised the image of PW2 SEL as the “manager” and that PW2 SEL had earlier testified in court). Despite alleging that he received a discount if he placed more bets, the Accused claimed that he was unable to state the percentage of discount he received.[^65]

37     The Accused claimed that payments of the bet amounts were made either in cash or cheques to PW2 SEL together with the repayment of loans the Accused had obtained from PW3 LKC. The Accused further stated that it was common practice for PW3 LKC to lend the Accused money when the Accused needed money and for the Accused to reciprocate by lending money to PW3 LKC when PW3 LKC needed money.[\[note: 66\]](#Ftn_66) No records were produced of the alleged loans between the Accused and PW3 LKC. The Accused claimed that the bulk of the amounts stated in the cheques were repayments of loans to PW3 LKC and that the bet amounts formed a very small proportion (if any). In respect of the $129,377 passed to the Accused, he claimed that this was money that was owed by PW3 LKC to the Accused and an additional sum the Accused had borrowed from PW3 LKC for the trade of his sand business Tri-M in Philippines.[^67]

38     The Accused testified that the Tri-M’s remittances to Philippines were raised by the shareholders for working capital. Remittances were made often up to one to three times a month[\[note: 68\]](#Ftn_68) over eight to ten years and that his brother Ng Eng Teck (also Tri-M’s director and shareholder oversaw the cash remittances to Philippines).[^69] At times the Accused suggested that he had borrowed from some of the Companies but was strangely unable to recall with certainty which Companies he borrowed from and when. I also note the Accused’s oscillating testimony from being unsure if he had repaid the loan he had taken from A Formation[^70] to claiming that he repaid $10,000 to $50,000 whenever he had money two to five times in a year.[^71]

39     In respect of Tri-M, the Accused further alleged that he had borrowed from his friends to fund Tri-M’s sand project in Philippines. Tri-M had invested more than $300,000 per year in securing sand mining rights in Philippines since the start of the company 10 years prior. The Accused was unable to identify with any precision the area of the initial mining rights (apart from it being near Sabah or Sarawak) or where the company was subsequently trying to obtain the right to mine (near Manila). The Accused nonetheless conceded that his contribution to the cash injections was 10% commensurate with his shareholding in Tri-M.

### DW2 – Ng Eng Teck

40     Ng Eng Teck (“**DW2 Ng Eng Teck**”), the Accused’s brother testified that he was a director and shareholder of Tri-M which invested in mining sand in the Philippines. He testified that Tri-M had four shareholders including Andrew Ong, Tan Yew Teck, the Accused and himself. At the point of testifying, Tri-M had been in operation for about 10 to 11 years

Each shareholder contributed cash injections to Tri-M commensurate with their relative shareholding in the company. From DW2 Ng Eng Teck’s recollection the Accused had contributed about $300,000 up till 2016.[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72) DW2 Ng Eng Teck, however, produced no clear documentary proof of the Accused’s 10% contribution to Tri-M.[^73] He further conceded that he was unable to verify where the Accused’s money came from as he never asked.[^74]

### SEL’s Statements

42     In the course of the trial, the Defence submitted that PW2 SEL’s knowledge on the Accused’s involvement as an “agent” was limited and that PW2 SEL did not know whether the Accused was PW3 LKC’s agent.[\[note: 75\]](#Ftn_75) The Defence contended that little weight, if any, ought to be attributed to PW2 SEL’s prior statements. The Defence alluded to various inconsistencies in PW2 SEL’s oral testimony in court, statements of fact (P9) and statements to the police (P10-P12) including:

> (a)     PW2 SEL initially testified that he knew that the Accused was collecting bets for PW3 LKC’s illegal gambling business and receiving price monies to be paid out for the business.[\[note: 76\]](#Ftn_76) Subsequently, PW2 SEL testified that he did not know the nature of monies PW2 SEL was delivering.[^77]

> (b)     PW2 SEL’s statement of facts (P9) states that PW2 SEL collected winnings and bets from the Accused “_once every week, for the entire period ranging from $1,000 to $5,000 on average_”[\[note: 78\]](#Ftn_78) whereas PW2 SEL’s statement to the police recorded on 29 July 2020 (P10) states that PW2 SEL collected or distributed money to the Accused once every two or three weeks.[^79]

43     In particular, the Defence pointed to PW2 SEL’s testimony that PW3 LKC never informed PW2 SEL that the Accused was PW3 LKC’s agent and his role was limited to collecting or delivering monies to individuals instructed by PW3 LKC.[\[note: 80\]](#Ftn_80) The Defence also pointed out that PW2 SEL’s testimony that he lacked clarity whether the Accused was an agent when he recorded his statements (P11 and P12).[^81]

### LKC’s Statements

44     In respect of LKC’s Statements the Defence disputed the accuracy of the four statements given by PW3 LKC to the police contending that the term “Dou Kia” meant both “punter” and “runner” in Teochew. PW3 LKC testified at trial he intended refer to the Accused as a “punter” when referring to the Accused as “Dou Kia” and clarified that the 10% commission referred to in the statement ought to have read a 10% discount given to the Accused instead.

45     The Defence referred to a material discrepancy between PW3 LKC’s statement to the police, P13, which stated that the Accused’s “_collection per_ _draw date_ _was about 7,000 to 8,000 worth of bets_”[\[note: 82\]](#Ftn_82) as opposed to “_$5,000 to $6000_ _a week_” in PW3 LKC’s statement to the police (P16)[^83] collection. The Defence also highlighted that this was inconsistent with statement in PW3 LKC’s statement of facts (P17) that the Accused’s “_collection per draw date was at least 5,000 to 6,000 worth of bets_”.[^84] The Defence contended that no clarification was obtained by PW4 Inspector Johnny on the discrepancy.[^85]

46     Additionally, the Defence highlighted that while PW3 LKC’s statement to the police (P13) only referred to _cash_ collected from the Accused[\[note: 86\]](#Ftn_86), PW3 LKC’s statement to the police (P16)[^87] and PW3 LKC’s statement of facts (P17)[^88] referred to _cheques_ issued for the illicit betting monies. The Defence submitted that the little weight, if any, ought to be attributed to PW3 LKC’s Statements given the inconsistencies highlighted.

47     The learned Defence counsel submitted two cases _PP v Liew Kim Choo_ \[1997\] 2 SLR 716 (“**Liew Kim Choo**”) and _Han Ying Ting v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2003\] SGHC 268</span> (“**Han Ying Ting**”) cautioning against undue reliance on the statement of facts of accomplices and statements to convict an accused.

48     In _Liew Kim Choo_ at \[88\]-\[89\] the Court expressed caution against relying on the statement of facts of an accomplice _alone_ to convict an accused. Essentially, the Court highlighted several reasons why an accused may plead guilty and admit to a statement of facts even if it contained facts that were untrue. This included situations where:

> (a)     a strong case had been formulated by Prosecution against the accused;

> (b)     the accused hopes to receive a lighter sentence by pleading guilty at an early stage;

> (c)     the accused is advised by his lawyers on the high likelihood of conviction; and

> (d)     the accused is unable to afford expensive representation in complex matters.

49     The court in _Liew Kim Choo_ further observed that the statement of facts is a supplement prepared singularly by the prosecution based on the evidence the prosecution has against the accused and was not subject to intense scrutiny to ensure its accuracy apart from ascertaining that the accused admitted to all material elements of the offence. As noted by the court at \[89\] it was “_unsafe to hang the …_ \[accused’s\] _conviction on the thread of the “immaterial” parts of …_ \[a co-accused’s\] _statement of facts_.”

50     In _Han Ying Ting_ at \[34\]-\[35\] the High Court highlighted that while previous inconsistent police statements were admissible as evidence of the facts stated within, the weight attributed to these statements would depend on the wholistic assessment of factors including (a) the accuracy of the statement (b) contemporaneousness of the statement and (c) maker’s incentive to conceal or misrepresent facts (see s 147(6) of the EA).

## The Law

### Section 5(a) CGHA

51     Section 5(a) of the CGHA provides:

> “**Assisting in carrying on a public lottery, etc.**

> 5.    Any person who —

>> (a)    assists in the carrying on of a public lottery;

>> …

> shall be guilty of an offence and shall be liable on conviction to a fine of not less than $20,000 and not more than $200,000 and shall also be punished with imprisonment for a term not exceeding 5 years.”

52     In _Bijabahadur Rai s/o Shree Kantrai v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 5 SLR 469</span> at \[28\] (“**Bijabahadur**”) the High Court highlighted that the term “_carrying on_” clearly illustrated “_the administration or running of a public lottery, not the mere participation in it_”. Section 5(a) of the CGHA did not apply to an individual who solely acts as a punter. As noted in the Second Reading of the Common Gaming Houses (Amendment) Bill, (State of Singapore, Legislative Assembly Debates, Official Report (13 May 1960), vol 12 (K M Byrne, Minister for Labour and Law) at col 721, the “_organisers of public lotteries are those who promote games …_”. It is patently clear that Parliament’s intent was to target individuals who organised, promoted or rendered assistance in the “operation” of a public lottery as runners, collectors or in any other capacity other than acting solely as a punter (_Bijabahadur_ at \[34\]).

53     For an offence under section 5(a) of the CGHA to be established the prosecution need not only prove (a) the accused’s purpose of assisting but also (b) the overt act relating to the carrying on of a public lottery. The former requirement may be established though circumstantial evidence illustrating, _inter alia_, an arrangement for the collection of bets, commissions or other benefits derived (see _Bijabahadur_ at \[36\]):

> “Such a purpose may be inferred from a variety of circumstantial evidence. The most common would of course be evidence of an arrangement between the bookie and the accused, whether for commission or otherwise, to **collect bets or to perform some other act connected with the carrying on of a public lottery** on the bookie’s behalf. Such an arrangement may in turn be inferred from **the circumstances of the case such as the collection of bets from all and sundry on behalf of the bookie, text messages between the bookie and the assistor, or evidence of any commissions or other benefits received by the assistor from the bookie** in connection with the assistance rendered.”

> \[Emphasis Added\]

54     In a similar vein, the overt acts committed by the accused must relate to the operation of the public lottery by, _inter alia_, “_promoting the lotteries, recording bets, collecting bets, paying out the dividends, chasing the punters for payment and financing or sponsoring the operations of the public lottery_” (_Bijabahadur_ at \[50\]).

55     To establish the s 5(a) CGHA charge against the Accused, the Prosecution must prove that the Accused between sometime in 2013 and 1 February 2015:

> (a)     intended to assist in the operation of a public lottery provided by PW3 LKC; and

> (b)     overtly acted to assist the operation of the 4D and TOTO lottery by receiving bets, communicating the bets received, collecting bets placed or distributing prize monies to individuals who won the lotteries.

### Section 9(1)(a) RGA

56     Section 9(1) of the RGA provides that:

> “**Providing unlawful remote gambling service for another**

> _9.—(1_)     _A person (called an agent) who, inside or outside Singapore —_

>> (_a_)     _organises, manages or supervises remote gambling by others in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent, which may include —_

>>> (_i_)     _inviting others to gamble using remote communication in accordance with those arrangements; or_

>>> (_ii_)    _placing, making, receiving or accepting bets using remote communication in accordance with those arrangements;_

>> (_b_)     _distributes a prize offered in remote gambling by others in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent;_

>> (_c_)     _distributes money or money’s worth paid or staked by others in remote gambling in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent;_

>> (_d_)     _facilitates participation by others in remote gambling in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent, which may include allowing a person to participate in such remote gambling; or_

>> (_e_)     _assists in any conduct described in paragraph (a), (b), (c) or (d)_,

> _and as a result facilitates one or more individuals to commit an offence under section 8, shall be guilty of an offence and shall be liable on conviction to a fine of not less than $20,000 and not more than $200,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 5 years or to both.”_

57     The legislative intent behind the enactment of the RGA is to curtail illegal gambling operations and its associations with syndicated transnational crime and other illegal activities. At its core, s 9 of the RGA is targeted at individuals “_who may not be remote gambling operators but are involved in some aspects of the operations, such as being an agent of a remote gambling operator_”. Agents would include individuals who facilitate remote gambling operations such as runners and bookies (see _Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report (7 October 2014) vol 92 (S Iswaran, Second Minister for Home Affairs_):

> “_Compared to terrestrial gambling, remote gambling gives us greater cause for concern for several reasons. First, from a law and order perspective, illegal remote gambling operators are typically associated with other criminal activities and syndicated crime. Remote gambling operations are lucrative and can potentially become a source or conduit of funds for money laundering and other illegal activities. These operations are transnational and of a significant scale, taking bets from many players across many countries. They offer credit and operate without any restrictions on the types of games or bets._

> _…_

> **_Clause 9 is aimed at persons who may not be remote gambling operators but are involved in some aspects of the operations, such as being an agent of a remote gambling operator._**

> _Clause 9(1) makes it an offence for an agent, whether based in Singapore or overseas, to facilitate an individual in Singapore to gamble with an unauthorised remote gambling operator._

> _Given the broader law and order concerns associated with remote gambling, clause 9(2) also makes it an offence for a person in Singapore to facilitate others overseas to gamble. It will cover agents, who are also known as bookies and runners, operating in Singapore but who may be receiving bets from overseas_.”

> \[Emphasis Added\]

58     For an offence under s 9(1) of the RGA to be constituted, any one of the subsections under s 9(1)(a)-(e) may be satisfied (_Khoo Moy Seen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 98</span> at \[9\]). An “_agent_” who facilitates one or more individuals to engage in unlawful remote gambling under section 8 of the RGA fully constitutes the charge. Section 5 of the RGA broadly defines “_remote gambling_” as gambling which uses remote communication such as the internet, telephone, television or radio or other electronic or technology to facilitate communication.

59     In light of the aforesaid, for a s 9(1)(a) RGA offence to be constituted the Prosecution must prove that the Accused acted as an agent between 2 February 2015 and 27 November 2016:

> (a)     Managing the remote gambling of punters according to the arrangements made by PW3 LKC by placing, making, receiving or accepting bets using remote communication; and

> (b)     Facilitated punters to engage in unlawful remote gambling.

### Section 5 OCA

60     The membership of a locally linked organised criminal group is an offence under s 5(1) of the OCA. The provision reads:

> **Locally-linked organised criminal group membership**

> 5.—(1)    Any person who is or acts as a member of a group, knowing or having reasonable grounds to believe that the group is a locally-linked organised criminal group, commits an offence and shall be liable on conviction to a fine not exceeding $100,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 5 years or to both.

> (2)    In determining whether a person is guilty of an offence under subsection (1), the matters which a court may consider include, but are not limited to —

>> (a)    that person’s involvement in meetings with other known members of the group;

>> (b)    whether that person is identified as a member by other known members (whether existing or former members) of the group;

>> (c)    whether that person adopts the style of dress, hand signs, language or tattoos used by known members of the group;

>> (d)    whether that person associates with known members of the group;

>> (e)    whether that person has recruited or attempted to recruit any other person to be a member of the group;

>> (f)    whether that person habitually visits premises or meeting places known to be used by the group, and the person knows or has reasonable grounds to believe that such premises or meeting places are owned or occupied by the group;

>> (g)    whether that person has been arrested more than once in the company of known members of the group for any seriousoffence that is consistent with the usual criminal activity of the group;

>> (h)    whether that person is identified as a member of the group by physical evidence such as photographs or other documentation;

>> (i)    whether that person has received or is receiving any financial or other material benefit from the group;

>> (j)    whether that person signed up to be a member of the group; and

>> (k)    whether that person has undergone any initiation ceremony or is subject to any disciplinary regime of the group.

61     A locally-linked organised criminal group is defined in s 2 of the OCA as a group, of at least three individuals “_however organised_”, whose purpose is to obtain a material benefit (financial or otherwise) or facilitate the commission of a “_serious offence_”. s 5 of the CGHA and s 9 of the RGA are listed as serious offences in the Schedule of the said OCA.

62     As highlighted in Parliament, the enactment of the OCA was primarily motivated to empower law enforcement agencies to deal with criminal syndicates in the context of their international operations. Similar requirements for three or more persons to form an organised crime group are set out in the United Nations Convention against Transnational Crime and other commonwealth jurisdictions including Canada, New Zealand and the United Kingdom (_Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Written Answers to Questions for Oral Answer not Answered by End of Question Time (12 January 2022) vol 95 (K Shanmugam, Minister for Law)_:

> **Mr K Shanmugam**: The Organised Crime Act (OCA) was enacted to strengthen the ability of our law enforcement agencies to deal with criminal syndicates.

> Criminal syndicates often operate across borders. Therefore, our approach towards organised syndicates has also taken into account international practices.

> Under the OCA, it is an offence to be a member of an Organised Criminal Group, which is defined as a group that **comprises at least three persons**, and has as one of its objectives, the obtaining of material financial benefits from the facilitation or commission of any serious offence listed in the Schedule to the OCA. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime, to which Singapore is a signatory, also defines an organised criminal group as three persons or more. Other jurisdictions, such as Canada, New Zealand and the United Kingdom also define an organised criminal group as one which comprises three or more persons.

> (Emphasis added)

63     For the offence under s 5 of the OCA to be constituted, the prosecution must prove that between 1 June 2016 and 27 November 2016 the Accused:

> (a)     with PW3 LKC and PW2 SEL acted as a member of a locally linked organised criminal group of three or more persons; and

> (b)     knew or had reasonable grounds to believe that the group’s purpose was to obtain a financial benefit or facilitate the provision of an illegal remote gambling operation.

### Section 11(1)(a) of the OCA

64     s 11(1)(a) of the OCA prohibits a person in Singapore from receiving, retaining, concealing, disposing of or dealing with property with the knowledge or reasonable belief that the property was illegally obtained by an organised criminal group. In the present case, the Prosecution will have to prove that the Accused knew or ought to have known that he was dealing with property illegally obtained by the organised criminal group by collecting and handing over monies to PW3 LKC and PW2 SEL.

## Issues to be determined

65     While it was largely undisputed that monies were transferred between PW3 LKC and the Accused in cash and cheques as set out at \[9\] and \[10\] above, the three key issues to be determined by the court is as follows:

> (a)     Whether PW3 LKC and PW2 SEL’s statements to the police and statement of facts ought to be relied upon by the court in evidence and the weight which ought to be attributed to these statements;

> (b)     Whether the Accused was an agent or a punter in the illicit gambling operations; and

> (c)     Whether the monies transferred between the Accused and PW3 LKC were an amalgamation of loans and personal bets placed by the Accused or illegal betting monies from punters.

## Decision

### Issue 1: PW3 LKC and PW2 SEL’s Statements to the Police and Statement of Facts

66     The Prosecution applied under s 147(3) of the EA to allow PW2 SEL and PW3 LKC’s previous statements to be used not only to impugn their credibility as witnesses but as evidence of the facts contained within the statement (see _Sim Bok Huat Royston v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2001\] 1 SLR(R) 588</span> at \[22\]).

67     Section 147(6) of the EA provides that the court in assessing the weight which ought to be attributed to a statement admissible under s 147 must consider all circumstances relating to the accuracy of the statement, questioning in particular the contemporaneousness of the statement and maker’s incentive (if any) to conceal or misrepresent facts:

> “Cross-examination as to previous statements in writing

> 147(6)    In estimating the weight (if any) to be attached to a statement admissible in evidence by virtue of this section regard is to be had to all the circumstances from which any inference can reasonably be drawn as to the accuracy or otherwise of the statement and, in particular, to the question whether or not the statement was made contemporaneously with the occurrence or existence of the facts stated, and to the question whether or not the maker of the statement had any incentive to conceal or misrepresent the facts.”

68     As noted by the High Court in _Sim Bok Huat Royston v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2001\] 1 SLR(R) 588</span> at \[24\] the examination of the recording officers remains an instrumental factor in determining the weight which ought to be attributed to the statement. The Court, however, is not restricted to the considering of only the circumstances surrounding the making of the statement but all circumstances affecting the statements’ accuracy by examining the inconsistent portions in context of the statement as a whole and the cogency and coherence of the facts relied upon (_Chai Chien Wei Kelvin v PP_ <span class="citation">\[1998\] 3 SLR(R) 619</span> at \[71\] (“**_Chai Chien Wei_**”)). A non-exhaustive list of factors aiding the Court’s assessment on the weight to be attributed these previously inconsistent statements is set out succinctly in _Chai Chien Wei_’s at \[71\] as follows:

> _“... First, the contemporaneity of a statement with the occurrence or existence of the facts stated is important for it guards against inaccuracy, though the degree of contemporaneity required will vary with the facts in question. The recollection of the details of particular events, particularly where these occur quickly, is easily susceptible to error with time but the recollection of the existence of a relationship is not so malleable. Second, there can be little guidance on the possibility of misrepresentation by the maker of the statement but the court must be astute in spotting such instances. Third, in addition to the above matters, the weight to be accorded to a prior inconsistent statement will be affected materially by an explanation of the inconsistency and why that statement is an inaccurate representation of the facts. Fourth, regard should be had to the context of the statement. Subsection (6) does not restrict consideration to only the making of the statement but requires consideration of all the circumstances affecting its accuracy. Thus the court must consider the context of the inconsistent portions, which requires that the whole of the statement be examined. Reliance cannot be placed on a portion of the statement that is taken out of context. Finally, the cogency and coherence of the facts to be relied upon has to be noted. An ambivalent statement does not attract much weight.”_

69     Applying these principles to the facts, I find that the term “_dou kia_” despite its dual meaning as “_agent_” or “_punter_” could not have been misunderstood by PW4 Inspector Johnny when recording LKC’s Statements (P13-P16). PW4 Inspector Johnny testified in court that he had clarified with what PW3 LKC meant by “_dou kia_” when recording his statements and that PW3 LKC used the word “_runner_” in English to refer to the Accused.[\[note: 89\]](#Ftn_89) Despite PW3 LKC’s allegations that he had intended to refer to the Accused as a punter _i.e._ “_dou kia_”, PW3 LKC made no attempt to amend his statements recorded on 9 December 2016 (P13), 8 May 2017 about five months later (P14), 26 December 2017 more than one year later (P15) and 22 February 2018 more than one year and two months later (P16). Pertinently, P13 was a contemporaneous statement given on 9 December 2016 for offences that had occurred between 2013 and 27 November 2016.

70     Turning to the possibility of misrepresentation, I see no reason for PW3 LKC to have falsely implicated the Accused who PW3 LKC regarded as his friend of more than 5 years.[\[note: 90\]](#Ftn_90) Further, there appears to be no reason or motive for PW3 LKC to implicate the Accused as, having implicated himself in his statements, PW3 LKC did not seek to minimise his role by shifting blame to the Accused.

71     As for the cogency and coherence of PW3 LKC’s Statements, there is little doubt that the material portions of P13-P16 clearly, unambiguously, and unequivocally establish that the Accused was PW3 LKC’s agent or runner collecting illegal bets and that the cash and cheques delivered through PW2 SEL were for the illicit 4D or TOTO.[\[note: 91\]](#Ftn_91) The minute details on the exact collections for each draw date or week or the modes of payment _i.e._ cash or cheques, even if vague or imprecise, did not detract from the core of LKC’s Statements implicating the Accused.

72     In a similar vein, whilst SEL’s Statements recorded on 18 May 2017 (P11), 29 May 2017 (P12) and 29 July 2020 (P10) were not entirely contemporaneous, this did not detract from its accuracy as it is unlikely that PW2 SEL’s memory of the events would have eroded with passage of time. SEL’s Statements did not require him to recollect a single remote incident but a prolonged state of affairs where PW2 SEL was personally involved in as PW3 LKC’s runner. As PW2 SEL’s last statement was recorded on 29 July 2020, after PW2 SEL had already pleaded guilty, I see no reason for PW2 SEL to implicate the Accused by misrepresenting material facts.

73     Whilst mindful of the dangers of relying _solely_ on previous inconsistent statements of a witness and the statement of facts to establish the Prosecution’s case let alone a conviction, I find that LKC’s Statements corroborate SEL’s Statements implicating the Accused. Further his account in his statement was also consistent with other documents adduced at trial. For the reasons set out above, I find that substantial weight ought to be attributed to the LKC’s Statements and SEL’s Statements recorded over a protracted period of approximately one year and three years, respectively. Evidence against the accused was buttressed by not one but two known convicted participants in the illicit gambling enterprise.

### Issue 2: Is the Accused a “Punter” or a “Agent” in the illicit gambling operations

74     Illicit gambling syndicates often operate a web of hierarchical structures. At the very top of the hierarchy is the “mastermind”. The illicit gambling enterprise is the brainchild of the “mastermind” who plans and directs these complex operations. Master agents hold illicit betting accounts and recruit agents to reach out to “punters”, colloquially known as gamblers betting in their personal capacity. Runners and bookmakers further facilitate the gambling enterprise syndicate by the collection and distribution of illegal betting monies in accordance with the recorded bets or odds..

75     In the present case, whilst it is undisputed that PW3 LKC was a master agent, and PW2 SEL was PW3 LKC’s runner collecting and distributing monies on PW3 LKC’s instructions, the key contention between the Prosecution and the Defence was in respect of the role the Accused played within the illicit gambling syndicate. The Defence’s position summarily is that the Accused was merely a “_punter_” placing bets in his personal capacity and not an “_agent_” or “_runner_” facilitating the syndicate’s operations.

76     The Defence’s assertions that the Accused is a “_punter_” and not an “_agent_” are at best an afterthought to underplay the Accused’s role in the illicit gambling syndicate. I set out three key reasons for my finding. First, LKC’s Statements (P13-P16) corroborate SEL’s Statements (P10-P12) and record in no ambiguous terms the Accused’s role as an agent or runner in the illicit gambling operations. PW3 LKC’s statement recorded on 9 December 2016 (P13) even detailed the Accused receiving a commission of 10% of the total bets and a further 5% on the winnings of the Accused’s punters. Collectively, seven statements taken at various points in the investigations from 9 December 2016 to 29 July 2020 all of which unequivocally implicated the Accused as an agent or runner in the illicit gambling operations. At no point, was the term “punter” or its equivalent used by PW3 LKC or PW2 SEL to describe the Accused to the three distinct police officers PW4 Inspector Johnny, PW6 ASP Tian and PW5 Inspector Khiang who recorded the statements over a protracted period of more than three years.

77     Second, little weight ought to be attributed to PW3 LKC’s oscillating and inconsistent oral testimony in court on the Accused’s placement of bets as an alleged “punter” and the movement of monies between the Accused and PW3 LKC. In PW3 LKC’s testimony in court PW3 LKC first alleged that the Accused placed bets with him[\[note: 92\]](#Ftn_92) before changing his narrative to the Accused “did not” place bets with PW3 LKC[^93]. In a similar vein, PW3 LKC had initially stated that all the cheques,[^94] including the cheque dated 25 March 2016 for the sum of $39,737, [^95] was money PW3 LKC had borrowed from the Accused. It was only when PW3 LKC was asked to look at the amount, that he changed his narrative that the sum of $39,000 could be monies borrowed and the remaining $737 could have been the bet amount.[^96] Again when referring to the $129,000 transferred between PW3 LKC and the Accused, PW3 LKC first stated that the $129,000 was monies the Accused was returning to PW3 LKC[^97] before altering his narrative yet again that the $129,000 was in fact monies he had borrowed from the Accused.[^98]

78     Third, contemporaneous records of messages recovered from PW3 LKC’s phone illustrate a series of instructions for PW2 SEL, PW3 LKC’s runner, to “collect” substantial amounts from the Accused. The present transactions are akin to the “collection” of bet amounts and not “loans”. A short extract of the messages referred to during the trial is set out as follows:

### Issue 3: Whether the monies collected and delivered between PW3 LKC and the Accused are loans or illicit gambling monies

80     Despite the Defence’s allegations that the monies transferred between PW3 LKC and the Accused were largely loans, there was no evidence adduced to prove that these monies shared the characteristics of a loan or any semblance of a loan transaction. There was neither any repayment schedule, nor agreed interest rate nor any record evidencing the purported loans made by the Accused to PW3 LKC. I found that the Accused was clearly lying to the court to cover up his misdeeds by dishonestly inventing the defence that the monies were loans.

81     I further observe that Accused’s IRAS statements for the years 2015 and 2016 states the Accused’s income as $71,499 and $79,539, respectively with an average monthly income of approximately $5700-$6400, after deducting the CPF life insurance. Notably, by way of cheques alone a sum of at least $189,737 is known to have been transferred from the Accused to PW3 LKC over approximately 11 months (_i.e._ 20 November 2015- 15 October 2016). The net monies transferred from the Accused to PW3 LKC between 20 November 2015 and 21 November 2016 (approximately one year) amounts to a substantial sum of at least $170,860. Contemporaneous records of PW3 LKC’s phone messages illustrate ghastly amounts of money collected from the Accused on PW3 LKC’s instructions to the tune of more than $1.7 million.

82     For completeness the contemporaneous records of the Short Message Services (“SMS”) in the _aide memoire_ compiled by the Prosecution which acts as a helpful guide on the monies transferred between the Accused and PW3 LKC is set out at Annex 2.

83     For the reasons set out above, I find each of the four charges against the Accused proven beyond any reasonable doubt by the Prosecution.

## Sentence

### Prosecution’s Submissions

84     The Prosecution alluded to the Accused’s fundamental role in a highly organised remote gambling operation which together with his contemporaries resulted in about $26.64 million in illegal bets channelled through the illegal gambling syndicate between 1 June 2016 and 27 November 2016. The Accused, as an agent, had earned commissions and profited from this illegal gambling business which mirrored SPL’s 4D and TOTO.

85     The Prosecution sought a global sentence of 30 months’ imprisonment and $70,000 fine as follows:

> (a)     18 months’ imprisonment and $26,000 fine for the s 5(a) CGHA offence (consecutive);

> (b)     20 months’ imprisonment and $44,000 fine for the s 9(1)(a) RGA offence;

> (c)     24 months’ imprisonment for the s 5(1) OCA offence; and

> (d)     12 months’ imprisonment for the s 11(1)(a) OCA offence (consecutive).

86     In support of the sentence of 30 months’ imprisonment and $70,000 fine, the Prosecution highlighted that the relative culpability of the Accused was akin to PW2 SEL, a runner under PW3 LKC, and Lim Poi Hwa (“**LPH**”), an agent under PW3 LKC. PW2 SEL was sentenced to 2 years and 16 months’ imprisonment and $108,000 fine. LPH was sentenced to 19 months’ imprisonment and $55,000 fine. The Prosecution also submitted that PW3 LKC was sentenced to 6 years and 36 months’ imprisonment and $447,000 fine for his role as a master agent in the illegal betting syndicate. The Prosecution also emphasised that the Accused in the present case claimed trial as opposed to PW2 SEL, PW3 LKC and LPH who pleaded guilty in a timely manner.

#### Section 5(a) CGHA Offence

87     In proposing a sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment and $26,000 fine for the s 5(a) CGHA offence, the Prosecution stressed that the Accused had acted as an agent for a shorter period of time and received a lower salary than PW2 SEL. The Accused acted as an agent for at least 13 months and earned approximately $26,000 in commissions from the $260,000 bets collected.

88     In comparison, PW2 SEL assisted in the carrying on of a public lottery from 2009 to 1 February 2015 and received a salary of $91,500. PW2 SEL was sentenced to 2 years’ imprisonment and $92,000 fine for the s 5(a) CGHA offence.

89     The Prosecution highlighted the Accused’s lack of mitigating circumstances and the need to disgorge the Accused’s earning from the illegal gambling operations.

#### Section 9(1)(a) RGA Offence

90     In respect of the s9(1)(a) RGA offence, the Prosecution submitted that the harm occasioned fell under the high end of low harm range and culpability fell under the low end of medium culpability range. The bets collected by the Accused were $440,000 based on a weekly calculation of $5000-$7000 a week. The Prosecution submitted that the Accused had acted as an agent for the illegal gambling syndicate for at least 22 months and procured a commission of approximately $44,000.

91     Based on a parity of sentence analysis the Prosecution submitted that the Accused conduct was far more culpable than PW2 SEL who acted as an agent for 22 months and dealt with $2,178.70 in bets without earning any commission but was comparable to LPH who acted as an agent under PW3 LKC. LPH had acted as a gambling agent from 2 February 2015 to 27 November 2016, collecting bets to the tune of $528,000 - $792,000 and a commission ranging from $52,800-$79,200. LPH was sentenced to 18 months’ imprisonment and $55,000 fine.

92     In light of the aforesaid, the Prosecution submitted for a sentence of 20 months’ imprisonment and $44,000 fine for the s 9(1)(a) RGA offence.

#### Section 5(1) OCA Offence

93     For the s 5(1) OCA offence, the Prosecution submitted for a sentence of 24 months’ imprisonment, an uplift from the 16 months’ imprisonment imposed on PW2 SEL and LPH. The Prosecution stressed the lack of mitigating factors such as the lack of remorse and the Accused’s failure to plead guilty in a timely manner.

#### Section 11(1)(a) OCA Offence

94     The Prosecution submitted that the Accused’s harm was on the low end of medium harm range and culpability at the middle of the low culpability range. The Accused had knowingly effected seven transactions dealing with $286,877 of property illegally obtained by an organised criminal group from 20 June 2016 to 21 November 2016.

95     In comparison with PW2 SEL’s role in the syndicate, as the chief runner for PW3 LKC, the Prosecution submitted that the Accused’s role was lower though the quantum dealt with by PW2 SEL ($327, 661) was comparable to the Accused.

96     The Prosecution submitted for a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment for the s 11(1)(a) OCA offence.

### Defence’s Submissions

97     The Defence in the Plea of Mitigation highlighted the Accused’s age as a 67-year-old man and his poor health and medical conditions such as thyroid disorder and hyperlipidaemia. The Defence also alluded to the Accused’s role as a filial son, devoted father, primary breadwinner for his family including his five children and his financial support for his siblings.

98     The Defence submitted that the appropriate sentence in the present case was a global sentence of 24 months’ imprisonment and a fine of $44,000 in parity with the sentences imposed on PW2 SEL, PW3 LKC and LPH. The sentences proposed by the Defence were as follows:

> (a)     12 months’ imprisonment and a fine of $26,000 for the s 5(a) CGHA offence (consecutive);

> (b)     15 months’ imprisonment and a fine of $18,000 for the s 9(1)(a) RGA offence;

> (c)     18 months’ imprisonment for the s 5(1) OCA offence; and

> (d)     12 months’ imprisonment for the s 11(1)(a) OCA offence (consecutive).

99     The Defence acknowledged that the Accused was not entitled to a discount given to individuals who had pleaded guilty but highlighted the expeditious conduct of the trial.

100    The Defence downplayed the Accused’s role in the illegal gambling syndicate. By drawing comparison with SEL’s Case for the s 5(a) CGHA offence, the Defence stated that PW2 SEL was involved in the illegal betting syndicate for a more protracted period (from 2009 to 2015) and earned more. The Defence also stated that whilst the length of offending was the same as LPH’s Case, in respect of the s 9(1)(a) RGA offence, the amount collected by LPH was far greater. The Defence again downplayed the role of the Accused in the s 5(1) OCA offence by stating that the Accused’s culpability was the same as LPH but lower than PW2 SEL despite acknowledging that both LPH and PW2 SEL were at about the same level in the organised crime group.

### Deterrence

104    The principle of general deterrence applies where an accused is engaged in a syndicated offence which is difficult to detect (_PP v Law Aik Meng_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 2 SLR(R) 814</span> at \[25(b)\] and \[25(d)\]). In _Koo Kah Yee v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGHC 261</span> at \[58\]-\[60\], Menon CJ, noted the difficulty of detecting remote gambling activities which often involved a syndicate cloaked in secrecy and other transnational elements. These aggravating considerations apply to the present case where there is little doubt that the Accused as an agent or runner participated in the illegal gambling syndicate with a sophisticated transnational element in Malaysia.

### Antecedent

105    The accused is traced, albeit, with an unrelated antecedent.

### DAC-913327-2019 (5(a) CGHA)

106    The non-exhaustive list of offence-specific factors the court may consider include:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="50%"><col width="50%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Harm Factors</b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Culpability Factors</b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Value of Bets</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Involvement of a Syndicate</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Transnational Element</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Difficulty of Detection</p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Degree of planning and premeditation</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Sophistication</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Offender’s role</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Personal gain</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Duration of offending</p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

107    As noted in _Lim Li Ling v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 1 SLR(R) 165</span> (“**Lim Li Ling**”) at \[92\] the value of the bets would be a key consideration in determining the sentence. The value of the bets allows the court to determine the scale of the illegal gambling operations.

108    In the present case, the estimated of the value of the bets collected by the Accused was $260,000 with a commission of $26,000 (10% of the bet value). The Accused knew that PW3 LKC was involved in a 4D and TOTO syndicate with operations headed in Malaysia. The Accused had participated in the illicit gambling operations as an agent or runner for a prolonged period from 2013 to 1 February 2015. The entire enterprise was carried out with considerable sophistication with bets placed through cryptic channels to a phone number in Malaysia and runners such as PW2 SEL ferrying monies between the Accused and PW3 LKC. The Accused derived a pecuniary benefit in the form of commissions on value of the bets placed by his punters.

109    The following cases on section 5(a) CGHA offences offer some guidance:

> (a)     In _SEL’s Case_, PW2 SEL pleaded guilty to assisting PW3 LKC to carry on public lotteries between 2009 and 1 February 2015. The value of the bets ranged from $5,000 to $50,000 each week. The total value of the bets collected by PW2 SEL from more than 10 agents ranged from at least $1,220,000 to $12,200,000. PW2 SEL was sentenced to two years’ imprisonment and a fine of $92,000 for the section 5(a) CGHA offence.

> (b)     In _PP v Or Poh Soon_ (DAC-941177-2017) the offender assisted PW3 LKC to carry on public lotteries between 2013 and 1 February 2015. The value of the bets collected was approximately $89,400 to $92,400 and a commission of approximately $7,212 to $7,512 was paid to the offender. The offender was sentenced to 8 months’ imprisonment and a $20,000 fine for the section 5(a) CGHA offence.

> (c)     In _Lim Li Ling_ the appellant pleaded guilty to a single charge under section 5(a) of the CGHA. On 26 November 2005, the appellant assisted in carrying on public ‘10,000 characters’ lottery using her sister’s laptop keying in bets received and transferring the data to an unknown location in Johor Bahru. The total bet value was $55,000. A sentence of 6 months’ imprisonment was upheld on appeal but the fine of $200,000 previously imposed was reduced to $80,000.

> (d)     In _Chia Cheng Hwee v PP_ (MA 287/91) (“Chia Cheng Hwee”) the offender pleaded guilty to one charge under section 5(a) of the CGHA for assisting with a 10,000 characters lottery on 7 August 1991. The bets collected by the offender was valued at $6,000. The offender was sentenced to 5 months’ imprisonment and a $50,000 fine for the section 5(a) CGHC offence.

110    The Accused’s conduct whilst not stemming from a single illegal bet as in _Chia Cheng Hwee_ and _Lim Li Ling_ cases, was less egregious than PW2 SEL’s conduct as an agent involving more than 10 agents, a higher weekly bet amount of up to $50,000 and a more protracted period. In light of the aforesaid, I imposed a custodial term of 16 months’ imprisonment and a fine of $26,000 (in default 6 weeks’ imprisonment) for this charge.

### DAC-913330-2019 (s 9(1) RGA)

111    In _Khoo Moy Seen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 98</span> (“**Khoo Moy Seen**”) Vincent Hoong J adapted the five-step sentencing framework, adopted in _Koo Kah Yee v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] 3 SLR 1440</span> (“**Koo Kah Yee**”), for a s 9(1) RGA offence. In deriving an appropriate sentence, using the five-step framework, the court must identify:

> (a)     the level of harm caused by the offence and offender’s culpability;

> (b)     the indicative sentencing band considering the harm and culpability matrix;

![](data:image;base64,)

> (c)     the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range;

> (d)     adjustments considering the applicable offender specific aggravating and mitigating factors; and

> (e)     further adjustments to the sentence in light of the totality principle.

112    Offence specific harm factors affecting the seriousness include (a) the total value of the bets (b) the presence of a syndicated enterprise (c) involvement of a transnational element and (d) difficulty of detection (_Khoo Moy Seen_ at \[17\]; _Koo Kah Yee_ at \[57\]–\[60\]). The factors affecting the culpability include (a) the level of planning and premeditation (b) the level of sophistication (c) the offender’s role within the organised or syndicated offence (d) any personal gain derived by the accused and (e) the duration of offending (_Khoo Moy Seen_ at \[20\]; _Koo Kah Yee_ at \[61\]–\[65\]).

#### Harm/ Culpability

113    In the present case, I assessed the harm occasioned by the Accused to fall under the lower end of the middle band. The bet amounts ranging from $18,000-$27,000 with a cumulative total of $189,737 is not insignificant. The offence was part of a syndicated enterprise involving the receipt and communication of bets via remote communication channels, bets placed in a Malaysian account held by PW3 LKC[\[note: 99\]](#Ftn_99) rendering it substantially more difficult to detect.

114    For completeness, I note that whilst the Prosecution submitted a cumulative total of $440,000 in illegal bets collected by the accused from 2 February 2015 to 27 November 2016, based on a weekly collection of $5,000-$7,000, this is merely an estimated projection. This has not been incontrovertibly established on the evidence presented at trial. As such, I am cautious to adopt the $440,000 cumulative total submitted by the Prosecution. Instead, I adopt the cumulative total of $189,737 in illegal bets established through a series of cash cheques issued and paid by the Accused to PW3 LKC or PW2 SEL (PW3 LKC’s runner) at \[9\] above.

115    In respect of the culpability, the culpability of the accused lies at the low end of the medium range. The Accused in the present case was an agent involved in the collection of bets, albeit, at the lower end of the hierarchy (cf _Public Prosecutor v Loy Jit Chan_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGMC 9</span> and _Public Prosecutor v Low Jing Da_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] SGDC 81</span> wherein the offender was a master agent and a high hierarchy agent, respectively, with “_master agent accounts”_ and the ability to create other agent accounts). The Accused was not the mastermind of the operations nor a master agent in a position to create other agent accounts. The Accused, however, did gain a pecuniary benefit from role in the syndicated operations as the Accused stood to earn approximately $18,974 in commission (approximately 10% commission on the bet amount of $189,737 being the value of the bets placed by the Accused with PW3 LKC between 2 February 2015 to 27 November 2016).

116    Given the harm placed is at the lower end of the middle band and the culpability of the accused lies at the lower end of the medium range, the indicative starting sentence is nine months to 2 years’ imprisonment. In addition to the custodial term, a fine is necessary to serve the twin functions of deterrence and retribution by disgorging any profits made by the Accused when facilitating the remote gambling activities (_Koo Kah Yee v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] 3 SLR 1440</span> at \[38\]-\[39\]; _Khoo Moy Seen_ at \[16\]).

#### Adjustments based on offender-specific factors

117    Whilst I note that the Accused has no relevant antecedents, I am careful to place any substantial weight on the Accused’s lack of antecedents. As the Accused’s illegal conduct spanned a prolonged period of at least 21 months from 2 February 2015 to 27 November 2016 (proceeded charge), the accused’s lack of antecedents may be attributable to the fact that the Accused was not caught earlier.

118    In light of the aforesaid, a sentence of 20 months’ imprisonment and the minimum fine of $20,000 (in default 4 weeks’ imprisonment) is sufficient to meet the ends of justice.

### DAC-913331-2019 (11(1)(a) OCA) and DAC-913332-2019 (5(1) OCA)

119    Turning to the secondary offence under section 11(1)(a) of the OCA, I find the present case less aggravating than PW2 SEL’s Case. The Accused had dealt with illegally obtained property amounting to $286,877 as compared to $327,661 in SEL’s Case. I further note that the Accused’s role within the syndicate was lower than PW2 SEL who was the primary runner for PW3 LKC. As such a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment (a downward calibration from the 16 months’ imprisonment sentence in SEL’s Case) is justified in the present case.

120    In respect of section 5(1) OCA offence, the Accused knowingly acted as an agent of a locally linked criminal group with PW2 SEL and PW3 LKC. In SEL’s Case and LPH’s Case, involving a runner and agent, respectively, a sentence of 16 months’ imprisonment was imposed. In the present case, given the Accused’s lack of remorse or compelling mitigating circumstances a sentence of 19 months’ imprisonment (an uplift of 3 months) is justified for the section 5(1) OCA offence.

## Conclusion

121    Given the totality principle and mindful that the sentence-imposed ought to be proportionate to the overall criminality of the Accused, I impose a global sentence of 28 months’ imprisonment and a fine of $46,000 (in default 10 weeks’ imprisonment) with the sentences for DAC-913327-2019 and DAC-913331-2019 running consecutively (_PP v Raveen Balakrishnan_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 5 SLR 799</span>).
